title Revived modules-and-aspects with the vane layer and the galaxy series; answered runtime-vs-SLC and the T-vane honestly
prompt Keaton asked whether the Glow runtime is more foundational and important than the SLC (since to be honest the SLC should be written in terms of it), whether to make a T-vane unifying Arvo's centrality and Vere (retiring or aspecting Caravan and Tally) with a different name (Tusk/Tilo/Toma/Toon, or a searched Urbit T-term), and then to revive the earlier modules-and-aspects active-designing writing, rewriting it to add vanes and the Glow OS small-PR-for-galaxies context.
think answered the foundational question on two axes rather than one: the runtime IS more foundational (everything stands on it) but the SLC is more important to ship now, and the "write the SLC in terms of the runtime to be honest" instinct is right in spirit yet already true in practice -- Pool P0/P1 use Caravan's capability table, the fold uses Tally-bounded memory, so the SLC is not floating free. Named the trap plainly: taken too far, "rebuild the runtime first" becomes rebuild-the-world-before-the-app, the design-over-build trap the finishing counsel warned of. The honest action is to name the dependency, not block shipping on a full runtime revival (Gall's Law: grow from working simples that already run green).
think collision-checked the four candidate T-names against the kernel: Tusk collides with the real Tusk/Narwhal/Bullshark DAG-consensus protocol (in our own gratitude shelf, adjacent to Neth); Toon collides with the real Hoon type ++toon (a virtualized-Nock result, runtime-adjacent); both ruled out. Tilo and Toma are clean (zero kernel and tree hits). Recorded the clean candidates but recommended holding the name.
think gave the honest verdict on the T-vane: the unify-Arvo-centrality-and-Vere idea is a legitimate Glow divergence (Urbit deliberately separates the pure kernel from the impure runtime) worth NAMING as a proposal, but it is the kernel/runtime not a vane (so "vane" is a slight category error), retiring Caravan (169 refs) + Tally (206 refs) is a ~375-ref boil-the-ocean migration, and it is design piling on design while the flagship rests. So: name the concept, hold the name and the build, keep the elders running -- consistent with the reviving discipline (defer to proven-supersede).
think revived the 20260702 modules-and-aspects doc as a new dated artifact beside the elder (accrete-never-break), keeping module/aspect/graduation-rule whole and adding: the vane as the system-concern host and the Glow four-letter family; the four-layer picture (aspect in module, module-as-agent in vane, vane in enclosure, enclosure on runtime substrate) proven green at its lowest rung by the Pool build; the runtime-unification proposal held; the runtime-vs-SLC judgment; and the galaxy small-PR framing (each layer a reference-sized, green-before-pitch, cheapest-first PR with a Galaxy Pitch block).
obs the doc ties the whole session's build and design threads into one coherent architecture picture for outside reviewers -- exactly what the galaxy-series contribution goal needs: each layer names its place, its size, and its witness.
obs "revive and rewrite" is a build-and-ship instruction across the two messages; committing to a branch and sending.
file active-designing/20260715-212500_modules-aspects-vanes-and-the-galaxy-series.md -- the revived doc: module/aspect/vane/runtime layering, the runtime-unification held proposal, runtime-vs-SLC, the galaxy small-PR framing
file active-designing/README.md -- newest-first row for the revived doc
file session-logs/20260715-212500_modules-aspects-vanes-revival.bron -- this log
recommend keep-going -- the architecture is now legible top to bottom for the galaxy series, the runtime-vs-SLC honesty is settled (ship the SLC on the runtime pieces already green; revive the runtime patiently), and the T-vane is a held, named proposal with clean candidates recorded. The next real work stays a choice: harden/package the SLC flagship toward a device or user, answer one Aurora/kelvin open question, or rest -- Keaton's word.
